          "body": "Verse 8 is the chapter's most revealing window into David's inner world. His protest to Achish — 'that I may not go and fight against the enemies of my lord the king?' — is technically a question, but it performs loyalty while allowing maximum ambiguity. 'My lord the king' is the phrase's pivot. Achish hears it as a reference to himself. The Hebrew reader, and any reader who has tracked the David narrative, knows immediately that David's true 'lord and king' is Saul — or more precisely, the LORD's anointed one, the office Saul holds. David has never in the entire book called Achish his lord and king. The narrator has given David a line that allows him to perform Philistine loyalty while maintaining — beneath the performance — the prior claim of Israel's covenant king. Whether David is consciously exploiting the ambiguity or whether the narrator is simply letting the language carry the story's irony, the effect is the same: David's protest is simultaneously his most honest speech in sixteen months and his last act of double-dealing. God does not wait for David to be transparent. He rescues him while he is still in the middle of performing the deception."
