          "body": "The chapter's final image is its simplest: 'So David arose early, he and his men, to depart in the morning to return to the land of the Philistines. And the Philistines went up to Jezreel' (29:11). Two movements, two directions: David south toward Ziklag, the Philistines north toward Jezreel and the battle where Saul will fall. These diverging trajectories carry the weight of 1 Samuel's entire narrative arc. Saul's story ends at Jezreel (ch. 31); David's story continues southward toward Hebron, toward anointing, toward Jerusalem. What looks like a retreat is actually a reorientation. God is not merely extracting David from immediate danger — He is moving His anointed king back toward the position from which Israel's monarchy will be rebuilt. The man who departed Gath heading north in the wrong direction now departs Aphek heading south in the right one, escorted out by pagan commanders who had no idea what they were doing."
