        "excerpt": "David and his men were proceeding on in the rear with Achish.",
        "body": "The opening two verses of chapter 29 land with quiet devastation. The Philistine armies are assembled at Aphek and moving north; David and his six hundred men are in the rear of Achish's column. This is not a brief tactical association. It is the culmination of sixteen months (27:7) of calculated deception that began when David 'said in his heart, \"Now I will perish one day by the hand of Saul\"' (27:1). The internal speech of 27:1 is the narrator's diagnosis: David's flight to Achish originated not in divine direction but in fear-driven human calculation. The same pattern appears in Abraham's flight to Egypt (Gen. 12:10-20), Elijah's flight to Horeb (1 Kgs. 19), and Jonah's flight to Tarshish — the people of God, under pressure, making geographic and moral choices that take them away from their calling rather than through it.\n\nThe phrase 'in the rear with Achish' is the chapter's spatial summary of David's spiritual and moral condition. In Israelite military order, the rear guard was a position of protection and support — but here it means David is trailing behind the enemies of his people, moving toward a battle against the nation he was anointed to rule. Robert Bergen (NAC) notes that the narrator places David in this position without editorial comment, trusting the reader's sense of dissonance to do the interpretive work. The dissonance is the point.\n\nThe chapter does not begin with David praying or confessing or seeking an exit. He is simply marching. The crisis he is in was assembled piece by piece over sixteen months of individually defensible decisions — each step seemed reasonable, and together they have produced an impossible situation. This is the pastoral warning the narrator embeds in the opening image: moral and spiritual drift rarely feels dramatic in the moment. It feels like survival. The accumulation is what becomes the crisis.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Acharon* (rear, v.2) — literally 'that which is behind or last.' The word's placement is the narrator's positioning irony: the future first king of a united Israel is at the back of the Philistine formation. *Machaneh* (army, forces) appears in both v.1 and v.6 — the same word describing the Philistine military machinery and, in v.6, the context in which Achish evaluated David. David has been absorbed into the *machaneh* of the wrong side."
