        "body": "The escape begins not with a divine appearance, an angel, or a miracle, but with the anger and military self-interest of Philistine commanders. Their objection to David's presence is entirely rational: a foreign mercenary in the rear guard, with a documented record of military prowess against their own forces, represents an unacceptable risk. Their reasoning in verse 4 is sound intelligence analysis — David could defect mid-battle and win back Saul's favor by presenting Philistine heads. Their citation of the victory song (v.5) demonstrates accurate knowledge of David's status in Israel. They are not wrong about any of this.\n\nThe theological weight is in the irony. God is using the political self-interest of Israel's enemies to accomplish what David could not accomplish for himself. The same victory song that created social division between Saul and David (1 Sam. 18:7-9) — the event that set the whole exile narrative in motion — is now, years later, the instrument of David's rescue from the crisis that exile produced. God is working through the full span of the narrative, redeeming even the painful history of the jealousy that drove David from Saul's court. What Satan (the adversary) intended for David's destruction — the public celebration that inflamed Saul's murderous jealousy — God has woven into the fabric of David's preservation.\n\nThe commanders' use of the word *satan* (adversary, v.4) in their military assessment of David is one of the chapter's most charged lexical moments. They fear David will become a *satan* against them. The reader who knows the fuller canonical story recognizes that the true adversary of God's covenant purposes has been attempting to destroy David throughout this entire period — through Saul's spears, through Doeg the Edomite, through the Philistines themselves. Here, the instrument the adversary would use (David fighting against Israel) is taken out of his hands by the very people through whom the adversary had previously worked.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Satan* (v.4) — adversary, opponent, one who hinders. Used here in its secular military sense, not yet as a proper name. The theological irony is that the Philistines are concerned about David becoming their obstacle, while the reader understands that the real obstacle to David's destiny has been David's own compromise. *Mecholah* (dances, v.5) — the victory celebrations of 1 Sam. 18:6, now cited as intelligence data by Israel's enemies. The same word spans both contexts."
