        "body": "Achish's dismissal speech is one of the most theologically dense passages in the chapter. He opens with the covenant name of Israel's God: 'As the LORD lives' (*chai Yehovah*, v.6). The oath formula is standard Hebrew — but it is on the lips of a Philistine king who has no covenant relationship with the LORD. What the narrator is doing here is signaling, through the precise vocabulary of the scene, that the God of Israel is the presiding reality over this conversation even though none of the participants acknowledge it. The LORD lives — the assertion of divine vitality and ongoing governance — is the invisible frame of the entire chapter.\n\nAchish then piles three moral evaluations on David: *yashar* (upright, straight, morally aligned), *tov* (good, pleasing) in his coming and going, and no *ra* (evil, bad) found in him. The irony, as noted in the observation steps, is that all three assessments are based on false information. David has been raiding non-Israelite peoples while reporting Israelite raids to Achish. The evaluations are sincere; they are also the product of sustained deception. Yet the narrator does not editorializing against Achish or mock him for his naivety. The effect is more complex: Achish becomes, despite himself, a witness to David's covenantal identity — the man who will become Israel's greatest king is evaluated, even by his deceived patron, in terms that echo the character requirements for Israel's leadership (cf. Deut. 17:14-20).\n\nThe word 'nevertheless' (*akh*, implied in the structure of verse 6b) is the hinge on which the entire escape turns. Achish's personal verdict cannot override the commanders' collective decision. This is the precise point at which God's instrument — the commanders' authority over the campaign — becomes irresistible. No amount of Achish's goodwill can reverse it. David is dismissed 'in peace' (*shalom*, v.7) — the fullness of wellbeing and completeness — by the king he has been deceiving. The grace of the dismissal is itself a form of providential kindness: God ensures that David exits this situation without violence, without exposure, and without the destruction of his reputation with Achish. The bridge back is not burned. That preservation of relationship matters — Achish will later receive David's loyalty again (2 Sam. 27:2-7 does not occur, but the relationship continues in 1 Kgs. 2:39-40).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chai Yehovah* (as the LORD lives) — the standard Hebrew oath by the divine name; appears frequently in David's own speech (1 Sam. 20:3; 25:26; 26:10). Here Achish uses it — the narrator's signal that the covenant God presides over what appears to be a purely Philistine political conversation. *Shalom* (peace, v.7) — wholeness, wellbeing, the absence of conflict. David departs in shalom from a situation that should have destroyed him."
