        "body": "David's response to the dismissal is a protest — and it is the chapter's most morally complex speech. He asks two questions: what has he done wrong, and what disqualifying fault has Achish found? The questions are technically unanswerable — Achish has already said he has found nothing (v.6). Then comes the crucial phrase: 'that I may not go and fight against the enemies of my lord the king' (v.8). The ambiguity is intentional and multi-layered.\n\nAchish hears 'my lord the king' as a reference to himself. This is the natural reading from Achish's position: David has been his vassal for over a year; the 'lord and king' in David's service would obviously be Achish. But every reader of the Samuel narrative knows that David has never transferred his primary loyalty to Achish. The LORD's anointing, the covenant established through Samuel (1 Sam. 16), and the repeated declarations of loyalty to Saul (24:10-11; 26:23) — all of these establish that David's 'lord and king' is the office of Israel's anointed. Whether David is consciously exploiting the ambiguity of the phrase or whether the narrator is simply allowing the language to carry the full weight of David's divided loyalties, the effect is the same: this is simultaneously David's most honest self-disclosure in sixteen months and his last act of linguistic deception.\n\nAchish's response in verse 9 — comparing David to 'an angel of God' (*maleakh Elohim*) — uses the highest possible compliment available in the ancient Near Eastern vocabulary of trust and reliability. Ironically, it is precisely the wrong metaphor. An angel of God executes divine purposes without deception, without self-interested calculation, without sustained false reporting. David is none of these things in this chapter. The compliment lands as the chapter's final irony: the most inflated praise of David's character comes from the person who knows him least accurately, immediately before David is dismissed from the chapter and the narrator moves him back toward his true calling.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Adon* and *melekh* (lord and king, v.8) — David uses both titles for his master, maximizing the ambiguity. *Maleakh Elohim* (angel of God, v.9) — a divine messenger who acts with complete integrity and divine authorization. The contrast between the compliment and David's actual conduct in the preceding sixteen months is the narrator's sharpest irony in the chapter."
