        "body": "The chapter's closing movement is brief and clean. Achish commands early departure; David obeys immediately. The urgency of 'arise early... as soon as you have light, depart' (v.10) mirrors the urgency of God's escapes throughout the Old Testament: early morning is the time of divine deliverance (Exod. 14:24-27; Ps. 46:5; Isa. 37:36). The narrator does not say the LORD commanded this timing — but the consistent canonical association of early morning with divine rescue is part of the texture of the scene.\n\nVerse 11's final image completes the chapter's theological argument with two simultaneous movements: 'So David arose early, he and his men, to depart in the morning to return to the land of the Philistines. And the Philistines went up to Jezreel.' David south; Philistines north. The divergence is the narrator's spatial theology. David is being moved away from the battle where Saul and Jonathan will fall — a battle he would have found impossible to navigate, whatever he chose to do. His absence from Jezreel is not cowardice; it is providential positioning. God preserves David from complicity in Saul's death, ensuring that when that death comes (ch. 31), David bears no responsibility for it (a fact the narrator will emphasize in 2 Sam. 1:1-16 when David executes the Amalekite who claims to have killed Saul).\n\nThe return 'to the land of the Philistines' is not a triumphant homecoming — it deposits David directly into chapter 30's crisis: Ziklag burned, families taken, men speaking of stoning him. But it is a return to a context where David can act as himself. In Philistia, he is a vassal in another man's army; back in Ziklag, he is the captain of his own men. The chapter that began with David in the wrong army ends with him heading home — still to Philistine territory, still not yet in Israel, but reoriented away from the battle that would have destroyed him, toward the sequence of events that will eventually bring him to Hebron and the throne.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shakham* (arise early, vv.10-11) — to load the shoulder early, to set out at dawn. The verb appears twice in the dismissal command and once in David's obedient execution of it — the triple occurrence marks the completeness of the departure. *Alah* (went up, v.11) — the Philistines go up to Jezreel; the same verb used of military advance throughout the chapter (v.9). The upward movement of the Philistines toward their battle and the downward movement of David toward the coastal plain is the chapter's final spatial theology."
